<h2 id="cfp">Call for Papers (<a href="http://www.sleconf.org/2023/CFP.html">source</a>, 46 taggings)</h2>
<p>
</p>
<h3>Topics of Interest</h3>
<p>
</p>
<p>SLE covers software language engineering rather than engineering a specific software language. Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:
</p>
<p>
</p>
<ul>
<li>Software <span class="term">Language Design</span><span class="tag" title="T1A: Design"><a href="../tag/t1a.html">T1A</a></span> and Implementation</li>
<ul>
<li>Approaches to and methods for <span class="term">language design</span><span class="tag" title="T1A: Design"><a href="../tag/t1a.html">T1A</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Static semantics</span><span class="tag" title="T1B: Static Semantics"><a href="../tag/t1b.html">T1B</a></span> (e.g., design rules, well-formedness constraints)</li>
<li>Techniques for specifying <span class="term">behavioral/executable semantics</span><span class="tag" title="T1C: Behavioural Semantics"><a href="../tag/t1c.html">T1C</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Generative approaches</span><span class="tag" title="T4C: Vertical Transformation"><a href="../tag/t4c.html">T4C</a></span> (incl. <span class="term">code synthesis</span><span class="tag" title="T4C: Vertical Transformation"><a href="../tag/t4c.html">T4C</a></span>, <span class="term">compilation</span><span class="tag" title="T4C: Vertical Transformation"><a href="../tag/t4c.html">T4C</a></span>)</li>
<li><span class="term">Meta-languages</span><span class="tag" title="T3A: Meta-languages"><a href="../tag/t3a.html">T3A</a></span>, <span class="term">meta-tools</span><span class="tag" title="T4A: Workbenches"><a href="../tag/t4a.html">T4A</a></span>, <span class="term">language workbenches</span><span class="tag" title="T4A: Workbenches"><a href="../tag/t4a.html">T4A</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Software Language Validation</span><span class="tag" title="T5D: Formal Methods"><a href="../tag/t5d.html">T5D</a></span></li>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">Verification and formal methods for languages</span><span class="tag" title="T5D: Formal Methods"><a href="../tag/t5d.html">T5D</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Testing techniques for languages</span><span class="tag" title="T5C: Testing"><a href="../tag/t5c.html">T5C</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Simulation techniques for languages</span><span class="tag" title="T4E: Simulation"><a href="../tag/t4e.html">T4E</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Software Language Integration and Composition</span><span class="tag" title="T1D: Composition"><a href="../tag/t1d.html">T1D</a></span></li>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">Coordination of heterogeneous languages and tools</span><span class="tag" title="T1D: Composition"><a href="../tag/t1d.html">T1D</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Mappings between languages</span><span class="tag" title="T4B: Horizontal Transformation"><a href="../tag/t4b.html">T4B</a></span> (incl. <span class="term">transformation languages</span><span class="tag" title="T3B: Transformation Languages"><a href="../tag/t3b.html">T3B</a></span>)</li>
<li><span class="term">Traceability between languages</span><span class="tag" title="T5G: Traceability"><a href="../tag/t5g.html">T5G</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Deployment of languages to different platforms</span><span class="tag" title="T2D: Deployment"><a href="../tag/t2d.html">T2D</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Software Language Maintenance</span><span class="tag" title="T2B: Evolution"><a href="../tag/t2b.html">T2B</a></span></li>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">Software language reuse</span><span class="tag" title="T1E: Reuse"><a href="../tag/t1e.html">T1E</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Language evolution</span><span class="tag" title="T2B: Evolution"><a href="../tag/t2b.html">T2B</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Language families and variability, language and software product lines</span><span class="tag" title="T2C: Variability"><a href="../tag/t2c.html">T2C</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Domain-specific approaches</span><span class="tag" title="T3C: DSLs"><a href="../tag/t3c.html">T3C</a></span> for any aspects of SLE (<span class="term">design</span><span class="tag" title="T1A: Design"><a href="../tag/t1a.html">T1A</a></span>, implementation, <span class="term">validation</span><span class="tag" title="T5D: Formal Methods"><a href="../tag/t5d.html">T5D</a></span>, <span class="term">maintenance</span><span class="tag" title="T2B: Evolution"><a href="../tag/t2b.html">T2B</a></span>)</li>
<li><span class="term">Empirical evaluation</span><span class="tag" title="T5E: Empirical Evaluation"><a href="../tag/t5e.html">T5E</a></span> and <span class="term">experience reports</span><span class="tag" title="T6A: Experience Reports"><a href="../tag/t6a.html">T6A</a></span> of language engineering tools</li>
<ul>
<li>User studies evaluating <span class="term">usability</span><span class="tag" title="T5H: Usability"><a href="../tag/t5h.html">T5H</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Performance benchmarks</span><span class="tag" title="T5F: Performance"><a href="../tag/t5f.html">T5F</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Industrial applications</span><span class="tag" title="T6B: Industrial"><a href="../tag/t6b.html">T6B</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Synergies between Language Engineering and emerging/promising research areas</span><span class="tag" title="T6D: Synergies"><a href="../tag/t6d.html">T6D</a></span></li>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">AI and ML language engineering</span><span class="tag" title="T6C: SLE-for-AI"><a href="../tag/t6c.html">T6C</a></span> (e.g., <span class="term">ML compiler testing</span><span class="tag" title="T6C: SLE-for-AI"><a href="../tag/t6c.html">T6C</a></span>, <span class="term">code classification</span><span class="tag" title="T6C: SLE-for-AI"><a href="../tag/t6c.html">T6C</a></span>) <span class="term">Quantum language engineering</span><span class="tag" title="T6E: Quantum"><a href="../tag/t6e.html">T6E</a></span> (e.g., <span class="term">language design</span><span class="tag" title="T1A: Design"><a href="../tag/t1a.html">T1A</a></span> for quantum machines)</li>
<li><span class="term">Language engineering for physical systems (e.g., CPS, IoT, digital twins)</span><span class="tag" title="T6F: CPS/IoT/DT"><a href="../tag/t6f.html">T6F</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Socio-technical systems and language engineering</span><span class="tag" title="T6G: Socio-technical"><a href="../tag/t6g.html">T6G</a></span> (e.g., <span class="term">language evolution</span><span class="tag" title="T2B: Evolution"><a href="../tag/t2b.html">T2B</a></span> to adapt to <span class="term">social requirements</span><span class="tag" title="T5A: Requirements"><a href="../tag/t5a.html">T5A</a></span>)</li>
<li>Etc.</li>
</ul>
</ul>
<p>
</p>
<h3>Types of Submissions</h3>
<p>
</p>
<p>SLE accepts the following types of papers:
</p>
<p>
</p>
<ul>
<li>Research papers: These are “traditional” papers detailing research contributions to SLE. Papers may range from 6 to 12 pages in length and may optionally include 2 further pages of bibliography/appendices. Papers will be reviewed with an understanding that some results do not need 12 full pages and may be fully described in fewer pages.</li>
<li>New ideas/vision papers: These papers may describe new, unconventional software language engineering research positions or approaches that depart from standard practice. They can describe well-defined research ideas that are at an early stage of investigation. They could also provide new evidence to challenge common wisdom, present new unifying theories about existing SLE research that provides novel insight or that can lead to the development of new technologies or approaches, or apply SLE technology to radically new application areas. New ideas/vision papers must not exceed 5 pages and may optionally include 1 further page of bibliography/appendices.</li>
<li>SLE Body of Knowledge: The SLE Body of Knowledge (SLEBoK) is a community-wide effort to provide a unique and comprehensive description of the concepts, best practices, tools, and methods developed by the SLE community. In this respect, the SLE conference will accept surveys, essays, open challenges, <span class="term">empirical observations</span><span class="tag" title="T5E: Empirical Evaluation"><a href="../tag/t5e.html">T5E</a></span>, and <span class="term">case study</span><span class="tag" title="T6A: Experience Reports"><a href="../tag/t6a.html">T6A</a></span> papers on the SLE topics. These can focus on, but are not limited to, methods, techniques, best practices, and teaching approaches. Papers in this category can have up to 20 pages, including bibliography/appendices.</li>
<li>Tool papers: These papers focus on the tooling aspects often forgotten or neglected in research papers. A good tool paper focuses on practical insights that will <span class="term">likely be useful to other implementers or users in the future</span><span class="tag" title="T1E: Reuse"><a href="../tag/t1e.html">T1E</a></span>. Any of the SLE topics of interest are appropriate areas for tool demonstrations. Submissions must not exceed 5 pages and may optionally include 1 further page of bibliography/appendices. They may optionally include an appendix with a demo outline/screenshots and/or a short video/screencast illustrating the tool.</li>
</ul><h2 id="lop">List of Papers (2+20, <a href="https://dblp.org/db/conf/sle/sle2023.html">source</a>)</h2>
<ul class="lop">

<li><em><a href="paper01.html">Exceptions all Over the Shop: Modular, Customizable, Language-Independent Exception Handling Layer</a></em> (<a href="../profile/WalterCazzola.html">Walter Cazzola</a>, <a href="../profile/LucaFavalli.html">Luca Favalli</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper proposes a modular, language-independent exception-handling layer that can be plugged into different language implementations.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL" title="Exception handling is defined as a reusable semantic layer that affects program execution behavior at runtime.">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The contribution is motivated and validated through a language evolution scenario extending existing languages with new exception features.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper02.html">An Executable Semantics for Faster Development of Optimizing Python Compilers</a></em> (<a href="../profile/OlivierMelançon.html">Olivier Melançon</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcFeeley.html">Marc Feeley</a>, <a href="../profile/ManuelSerrano.html">Manuel Serrano</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagM" title="The main contribution is an executable (formal) semantics for Python that serves as a reference for understanding and implementing the language.">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The semantics is used to speed up development of optimizing compilers, i.e., downstream compilation and refinement pipelines.">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work is grounded in semantic specification/validation techniques typical of formal methods for programming languages.">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper03.html">Adaptive Structural Operational Semantics</a></em> (<a href="../profile/GwendalJouneaux.html">Gwendal Jouneaux</a>, <a href="../profile/DamianFrölich.html">Damian Frölich</a>, <a href="../profile/OlivierBarais.html">Olivier Barais</a>, <a href="../profile/BenoîtCombemale.html">Benoît Combemale</a>, <a href="../profile/GurvanLeGuernic.html">Gurvan Le Guernic</a>, <a href="../profile/GunterMussbacher.html">Gunter Mussbacher</a>, <a href="../profile/LThomasvanBinsbergen.html">L. Thomas van Binsbergen</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper introduces a variant of structural operational semantics aimed at specifying adaptive program behavior.">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The semantics explicitly targets runtime adaptation mechanisms that influence execution during operation.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The motivation is to make self-adaptation easier to add in domain-specific settings where adaptation is a secondary concern.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><span title="Keynote">🔥</span> <em><a href="keynote1.html">Coccinelle: Impact and Internals</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JuliaLawall.html">Julia Lawall</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM" title="The keynote’s subject is a program matching and transformation tool, and the main story is about transformation at scale in real codebases.">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Its headline evidence is long-term maintenance work on the Linux kernel (thousands of commits), i.e., evolution via automated refactorings/patches.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The talk is grounded in industrial-scale practice (real-world adoption and sustained use on a flagship system).">T6B: Industrial</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="It discusses tool internals and design decisions enabling these transformations, making tooling/infrastructure a major aspect.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper04.html">A Reference GLL Implementation</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AdrianJohnstone.html">Adrian Johnstone</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper delivers a reference implementation of the GLL parsing algorithm intended as a baseline tool for the community.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="A key purpose is enabling fair performance comparisons of optimized GLL variants against a common baseline.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work frames the implementation as an evaluation baseline for empirical comparisons across implementations.">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper05.html">Sharing Trees and Contextual Information: Re-imagining Forwarding in Attribute Grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LucasKramer.html">Lucas Kramer</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The contribution is a technique within the attribute-grammar meta-language paradigm for structuring and reusing semantic computations.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Forwarding and contextual information sharing primarily concern static analyses such as name resolution and type checking.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work emphasizes modular feature extensions by translating new features to a core while sharing analysis results.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper06.html">Nanopass Attribute Grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/NathanRingo.html">Nathan Ringo</a>, <a href="../profile/LucasKramer.html">Lucas Kramer</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper adapts the nanopass compiler architecture using attribute grammars to structure multi-stage compilation and lowering.">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="Attribute grammars serve as the meta-language used to specify analyses and transformations across passes.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Many nanopass stages encode static semantic checks/analyses over intermediate language variants.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper07.html">Automated Extraction of Grammar Optimization Rule Configurations for Metamodel-Grammar Co-evolution</a></em> (<a href="../profile/WeixingZhang.html">Weixing Zhang</a>, <a href="../profile/ReginaHebig.html">Regina Hebig</a>, <a href="../profile/DanielStrüber.html">Daniel Strüber</a>, <a href="../profile/JanPhilippSteghöfer.html">Jan-Philipp Steghöfer</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM" title="The focus is on supporting co-evolution of metamodels and grammars by automatically extracting and updating grammar optimization configurations.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The technique analyses and manipulates grammar specifications to recover optimization-rule configurations.">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Grammar migration after metamodel changes is framed as a systematic transformation/mapping problem between artefacts.">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper08.html">Reuse and Automated Integration of Recommenders for Modelling Languages</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LissetteAlmonte.html">Lissette Almonte</a>, <a href="../profile/AntonioGarmendía.html">Antonio Garmendía</a>, <a href="../profile/EstherGuerra.html">Esther Guerra</a>, <a href="../profile/JuandeLara.html">Juan de Lara</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagM" title="The core contribution is enabling reuse of recommenders across modelling languages and reducing duplication when integrating them.">T1E: Reuse</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The paper proposes infrastructure to integrate recommenders into modelling tools with less engineering effort.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The setting is modelling languages (DSLs), for which recommendation services are built and reused.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper09.html">GPT-3-Powered Type Error Debugging: Investigating the Use of Large Language Models for Code Repair</a></em> (<a href="../profile/FranciscoRibeiro.html">Francisco Ribeiro</a>, <a href="../profile/JoséNunoMacedo.html">José Nuno Macedo</a>, <a href="../profile/KanaeTsushima.html">Kanae Tsushima</a>, <a href="../profile/RuiAbreu.html">Rui Abreu</a>, <a href="../profile/JoãoSaraiva.html">João Saraiva</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4g.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper investigates using large language models (GPT-3) to assist with type-error debugging and code repair in language tooling.">T4G: AI-for-SLE</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The target problems are type errors and their diagnosis, which are rooted in static semantics and type systems.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="The motivation is improving the usefulness of compiler feedback and reducing developer effort in debugging type errors.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper10.html">Temporal Breakpoints for Multiverse Debugging</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MatthiasPasquier.html">Matthias Pasquier</a>, <a href="../profile/CiprianTeodorov.html">Ciprian Teodorov</a>, <a href="../profile/FrédéricJouault.html">Frédéric Jouault</a>, <a href="../profile/MatthiasBrun.html">Matthias Brun</a>, <a href="../profile/LukaLeRoux.html">Luka Le Roux</a>, <a href="../profile/LoïcLagadec.html">Loïc Lagadec</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper extends multiverse debugging with temporal breakpoints, advancing debugging/testing support for exploring executions.">T5C: Testing</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL" title="Breakpoints are defined over runtime execution traces of nondeterministic/concurrent programs.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5g.html"><span class="tagL" title="Temporal breakpoints rely on richer temporal properties over execution histories, strengthening trace-based reasoning.">T5G: Traceability</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper11.html">Cross-Level Debugging for Static Analysers</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MatsVanMolle.html">Mats Van Molle</a>, <a href="../profile/BramVandenbogaerde.html">Bram Vandenbogaerde</a>, <a href="../profile/CoenDeRoover.html">Coen De Roover</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The contribution targets debugging of static analysers, which are formal-methods-style tools that compute sound/terminating program properties.">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work provides tooling support to debug the analyser implementation by relating analysis-level and program-level executions.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="It aims to improve the developer experience of diagnosing and fixing bugs in static analysis tools via better debugging support.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper12.html">Cascade: A Meta-language for Change, Cause and Effect</a></em> (<a href="../profile/RiemervanRozen.html">Riemer van Rozen</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM" title="Cascade is presented as a meta-language for expressing change, cause-and-effect, and interpreter behavior for DSLs.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The meta-language is explicitly aimed at creating and retrofitting domain-specific languages with live-programming features.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The approach relies on (bi-directional) model transformations and migrations to represent and propagate change.">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The accompanying runtime (Delta) executes transformations and maintains histories during program execution.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><span title="Keynote">🔥</span> <em><a href="keynote2.html">Artificial Languages are Dead. Long Live Artificial Languages!</a></em> (<a href="../profile/CristinaVideiraLopes.html">Cristina Videira Lopes</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t6c.html"><span class="tagM" title="The keynote is explicitly about how AI/LLMs change the relationship between programming and AI—i.e., language engineering for an AI-shaped software development world (including education implications).">T6C: SLE-for-AI</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4g.html"><span class="tagL" title="LLMs doing translation from natural language/specifications to code is AI-driven automation directly affecting language use and tooling.">T4G: AI-for-SLE</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The framing is broadly cross-cutting (practice + fundamental notions of programming + CS education), i.e., a field-level synthesis/agenda piece.">T6D: Synergies</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper13.html">Seamless Code Generator Synchronization in the Composition of Heterogeneous Modeling Languages</a></em> (<a href="../profile/NicoJansen.html">Nico Jansen</a>, <a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper addresses composition of heterogeneous modeling languages, focusing on synchronizing their code generators and artefacts.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL" title="Code generator synchronization is fundamentally about coordinating generative/compilation pipelines across composed languages.">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The solution is positioned as practical infrastructure for language/tool engineering rather than a one-off implementation.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper14.html">Enabling Blended Modelling of Timing and Variability in EAST-ADL</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MuhammadWaseemAnwar.html">Muhammad Waseem Anwar</a>, <a href="../profile/FedericoCiccozzi.html">Federico Ciccozzi</a>, <a href="../profile/AlessioBucaioni.html">Alessio Bucaioni</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM" title="The work extends and supports the EAST-ADL domain-specific modelling language with blended modelling facilities.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagL" title="A major concern is variability modelling, which aligns with product-line style variability management.">T2C: Variability</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6f.html"><span class="tagL" title="EAST-ADL targets automotive embedded systems, placing the contribution in a CPS/IoT domain context.">T6F: CPS/IoT/DT</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL" title="Blended modelling involves multiple concrete syntaxes (often including graphical views), making visual interaction a secondary concern.">T4F: Visualisation</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper15.html">Towards Efficient Model Comparison using Automated Program Rewriting</a></em> (<a href="../profile/QuratUlAinAli.html">Qurat Ul Ain Ali</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/KonstantinosBarmpis.html">Konstantinos Barmpis</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper proposes a model comparison approach, which is a horizontal mapping/differencing operation between models.">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The comparison is encoded in a rule-based language and optimized via automated program rewriting of those rules.">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="The main driver is improving efficiency of comparison for large models, making performance a key evaluation axis.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper16.html">Deriving Integrated Multi-Viewpoint Modeling Languages from Heterogeneous Modeling Languages: An Experience Report</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MalteHeithoff.html">Malte Heithoff</a>, <a href="../profile/NicoJansen.html">Nico Jansen</a>, <a href="../profile/JörgChristianKirchhof.html">Jörg Christian Kirchhof</a>, <a href="../profile/JudithMichael.html">Judith Michael</a>, <a href="../profile/FlorianRademacher.html">Florian Rademacher</a>, <a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t6a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper is explicitly an experience report on deriving integrated multi-viewpoint modelling languages in practice.">T6A: Experience Reports</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The experience centers on integrating multiple heterogeneous viewpoints/languages into a cohesive modelling language.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The subject matter is modelling languages used by domain experts, i.e., DSL engineering practice.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper17.html">A Low-Code Platform for Systematic Component-Oriented Language Composition</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JérômePfeiffer.html">Jérôme Pfeiffer</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreasWortmann.html">Andreas Wortmann</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The main contribution is a low-code platform (tool) that supports systematic component-oriented language composition.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The platform operationalizes language composition mechanisms by coordinating multiple language constituents (syntax and semantics).">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL" title="The approach relies on a graphical, web-based interface typical of visualization-oriented tooling.">T4F: Visualisation</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper18.html">A Tool for the Definition and Deployment of Platform-Independent Bots on Open Source Projects</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AdemAit.html">Adem Ait</a>, <a href="../profile/JavierLuisCánovasIzquierdo.html">Javier Luis Cánovas Izquierdo</a>, <a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t2d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper focuses on defining and deploying bots in a platform-independent way across open-source projects.">T2D: Deployment</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The contribution is realized as a toolchain for specifying bots and deploying them to target repositories.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The bot definitions resemble a domain-specific specification language for project automation tasks.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper19.html">Online Name-Based Navigation for Software Meta-languages</a></em> (<a href="../profile/PeterDMosses.html">Peter D. Mosses</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper provides tooling for precise name-based navigation of meta-language specifications in online repositories.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The target artefacts are specifications written in meta-languages used for language definition and implementation.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="The goal is to improve usability when browsing and understanding language specifications via web-based navigation.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper20.html">Practical Runtime Instrumentation of Software Languages: The Case of SciHook</a></em> (<a href="../profile/DorianLeroy.html">Dorian Leroy</a>, <a href="../profile/BenoîtCombemale.html">Benoît Combemale</a>, <a href="../profile/BenoîtLelandais.html">Benoît Lelandais</a>, <a href="../profile/MariePierreOudot.html">Marie-Pierre Oudot</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper proposes practical runtime instrumentation to enable interoperability between software languages during execution.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="Interoperability across languages is treated as an integration problem, bridging otherwise siloed language runtimes.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5g.html"><span class="tagL" title="Defining a behavioral interface and instrumenting executions provides traceable runtime interactions between languages.">T5G: Traceability</span></a>
</li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="org">Organisers</h2><ul><li><a href="../profile/JoãoSaraiva.html">João Saraiva</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">General Chair</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/ThomasDegueule.html">Thomas Degueule</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">Programme Chair</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/ElizabethScott.html">Elizabeth Scott</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">Programme Chair</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/CasperBachPoulsen.html">Casper Bach Poulsen</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/JeanChristopheBach.html">Jean-Christophe Bach</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/HoratiuCirstea.html">Horatiu Cirstea</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/DavideDiRuscio.html">Davide Di Ruscio</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/RominaEramo.html">Romina Eramo</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/FelienneHermans.html">Felienne Hermans</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/committee/sle-2023-program-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/RobertHirschfeld.html">Robert Hirschfeld</a> (<a href="https://2023.splashco